      "content": "It's possible that your sourdough starter is slow-developing, as many starters need patience and warm temperatures to thrive. At 70 degrees, it might take longer than you expected. Fermentation is a natural process, and clumping around the feeding with rye flour can also hinder its growth. Try feeding your starter with equal parts of flour and water every 12-24 hours and consider getting it to room temperature when you feed it. Keep an eye on it, be patient, and let the natural yeast do its work!",
