    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "70 degrees seems okay for most things but i'm worried it's too cold for the yeast. also the texture is kind of weird/lumpy lately instead of just being smooth liquid. should i add more water to thin it out or will that mess up the fermentation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It sounds like you're working in a cooler environment than a typical sourdough starter ideally requires, which is around 68-78 degrees Fahrenheit (20-26°C). To promote faster growth, you could try placing your starter in a warmer spot, like near a heater or in an off-heat oven with the light on. As for the lumpy texture, that’s completely normal for sourdough starters—they can lose their liquid as they multiply, which is why it becomes lumpy. Adding more water could thin it too much and may disturb the water-to-flour ratio vital for the microbes to thrive. Instead, try feeding them more often, which will also help maintain their smooth texture. Just continue to feed with equal parts of flour and water, and keep an eye on their progress. Patience is key when nurturing a sourdough starter.",
